QCC Data Warehouse and OBIEE Dashboards

Elisabeth Lackner and Patrick Wynne

January 26, 2018

Overview

  • Goal: governed self discovery

  • Data warehousing

  • Data governance

  • OBIEE reporting and analyses

Data Visualization/Presentation Spectrum

  • Data visualization falls on spectrum from exploratory to narrative, typically corresponding to the beginning and end of data analysis process respectively

  • IR writes flexible domain specific reports to crowdsource the exploratory data analysis (EDA) process across the campus community

  • IR then works with constituents to turn EDA into compelling and sound narratives

How

  • Collaboration between IR, IT, and senior administration

  • Create data warehouse from CUNY First Reporting Instance using Oracle tools (SQL Developer, Administration Tool, Business Intelligence Enterprise Edition)

  • Create data governance workflow for OBIEE using Data Cookbooks

  • Create reports and give read access to relevant parties

Data Flow

Data Warehouse

  • Scheduled queries from the reporting instance are the primary data sources, but the ETL is easily extendable to other data sources

  • The key feature is change data capture. Everyday the ETL compares todays data to yesterdays and records all changes. This allows us to recreate the warehouses state on any given day.

  • The change data capture allows us to create snapshot tables as part of the daily ETL recreating the warehouses state for prespecified times e.g.current offset, latest data, 10 days before the start of the semester etc.

Data Governance

  • A greenfield data warehouse project leads naturally to collaborative data governance

  • Replace legacy naming conventions (UNT_TAKEN_PRGRSS, UNT_TAKEN_GPA, UNT_TAKEN_PA, UNT_TAKEN_PA_GPA?) with intuitive alternatives

  • Establish a data dictionary workflow whereby IR/IT send data definitions and calculations to responsible departments for approval via Data Cookbooks
